{"count": 41722, "next": "https://api.acmi.net.au/works/?page=1440", "previous": "https://api.acmi.net.au/works/?page=1438", "results": [{"id": 118140, "acmi_id": "184732", "title": "TV miniatures", "title_annotation": "", "slug": "tv-miniatures", "creator_credit": "", "credit_line": "<p>Designed by Graham McGuffie<br />\nEmily Boutard and Megafun</p>", "headline_credit": "Australia, 2019", "video_links": [], "record_type": "work", "type": "Film", "is_on_display": true, "last_on_display_place": "ACMI: Gallery 1", "last_on_display_date": "2031-02-16", "is_context_indigenous": false, "material_description": "", "unpublished": false, "external": false, "first_production_date": "2019-01-01T11:00:00+11:00", "commissioned": false, "public_domain": false, "external_references": [], "brief_description": "<p>These six miniature dioramas reflect how home interiors changed to make way for TV across different decades, representing the common places people watched their favourite stories unfold on-screen.</p>", "constellations_primary": [{"id": 284, "name": "Nightly news and laughs", "description": "Throughout the decades on Australian screens, comedy and news have often gone hand-in-hand."}], "constellations_other": [], "recommendations": [], "title_for_label": "<p>TV miniatures</p>", "creator_credit_for_label": "", "headline_credit_for_label": "<p>Australia, 2019</p>", "description": "<p>Television didn’t just change the way we see the world; it changed the look and layout of our homes. Since TV arrived in Australia in the 1950s, how and where we watch TV evolved alongside its form and function. These six miniature dioramas, designed by Graham McGuffie and handmade by Emily Boutard, reflect how home interiors changed to make way for TV across different decades, representing the common places people watched their favourite stories unfold on-screen.</p>", "description_for_label": ["<p>Television didn’t just change the way we see the world; it changed the look and layout of our homes. Since TV arrived in Australia in the 1950s, how and where we watch TV evolved alongside its form and function. These six miniature dioramas, designed by Graham McGuffie and handmade by Emily Boutard, reflect how home interiors changed to make way for TV across different decades, representing the common places people watched their favourite stories unfold on-screen.</p>"], "credit_line_for_label": "<p>Designed by Graham McGuffie<br />\nEmily Boutard and Megafun</p>", "details": [{"label": "Curatorial section", "display_values": ["The Story of the Moving Image&nbsp;→ Moving Pictures&nbsp;→ MI-07. Birth of Television&nbsp;→ MI-07-AV01"]}, {"label": "Object Types", "display_values": ["Moving image file/Digital"]}], "stats": {"tap_count": 299433}, "links": [], "creators_primary": [], "creators_other": [{"id": 2686669, "name": "Graham McGuffie", "creator_id": 84711, "creator_wikidata_id": null, "role": "designer", "role_id": 495, "is_primary": false}], "media_note": null, "holdings": [], "part_of": null, "parts": [], "part_siblings": [], "group": null, "group_works": [], "group_siblings": [], "source": {"name": "Vernon", "slug": "vernon"}, "source_identifier": "184732", "eaas_environment_id": null, "production_places": [{"id": 3, "name": "Australia", "slug": "australia"}], "production_dates": [{"date": "2019", "notes": "", "to_year": "2019"}], "labels": [57642]}, {"id": 118043, "acmi_id": "184289", "title": "Videogames and Us", "title_annotation": "", "slug": "videogames-and-us", "creator_credit": "ACMI", "credit_line": "<p>Additional research by Dr Dan Golding</p>", "headline_credit": "Australia, 2020", "video_links": [], "record_type": "work", "type": "Object", "is_on_display": true, "last_on_display_place": "ACMI: Gallery 1", "last_on_display_date": "2031-02-16", "is_context_indigenous": false, "material_description": "", "unpublished": false, "external": false, "first_production_date": "2020-01-01T11:00:00+11:00", "commissioned": false, "public_domain": false, "external_references": [], "brief_description": "<p>Since videogames were first invented in laboratories, our relationship to play has evolved. From arcades and the first home consoles to today’s blockbuster releases, mobile games and experimental indies, how we interpret and experience vieogames has changed alongside us.</p>", "constellations_primary": [], "constellations_other": [{"id": 282, "name": "Arcades and AI", "description": "Using the godfather of computing, Alan Turing, as a starting point, this Constellation traces the evolution of AI representation on-screen and the way female androids, robots and holograms have been hyper sexualised."}], "recommendations": [], "title_for_label": "<p>Videogames and Us</p>", "creator_credit_for_label": "<p>ACMI</p>", "headline_credit_for_label": "<p>Australia, 2020</p>", "description": "<p>Play is an essential part of who we are as individuals and as a collective. Since videogames were first invented by scientists in laboratories, our relationship to play has come a long way. From arcades and the first home consoles to today’s blockbuster releases, mobile games and experimental indies, videogames have evolved dramatically and so have we. How we interpret and experience videogames, and the communities and cultures spawned from them, reveals much about how society has shifted in the past five decades.</p>", "description_for_label": ["<p>Play is an essential part of who we are as individuals and as a collective. Since videogames were first invented by scientists in laboratories, our relationship to play has come a long way. From arcades and the first home consoles to today’s blockbuster releases, mobile games and experimental indies, videogames have evolved dramatically and so have we. How we interpret and experience videogames, and the communities and cultures spawned from them, reveals much about how society has shifted in the past five decades.</p>"], "credit_line_for_label": "<p>Additional research by Dr Dan Golding</p>", "details": [{"label": "Curatorial section", "display_values": ["The Story of the Moving Image&nbsp;→ Games Lab&nbsp;→ GL-05. Videogames Infographic&nbsp;→ GL-05-C01"]}, {"label": "Object Types", "display_values": ["2D Object"]}], "stats": {"tap_count": 182803}, "links": [], "creators_primary": [{"id": 2686593, "name": "ACMI", "creator_id": 6272, "creator_wikidata_id": null, "role": "creator", "role_id": 968, "is_primary": true}], "creators_other": [{"id": 2686594, "name": "Dan Golding", "creator_id": 84443, "creator_wikidata_id": null, "role": "researcher", "role_id": 950, "is_primary": false}], "media_note": null, "holdings": [], "part_of": null, "parts": [], "part_siblings": [], "group": null, "group_works": [], "group_siblings": [], "source": {"name": "Vernon", "slug": "vernon"}, "source_identifier": "184289", "eaas_environment_id": null, "production_places": [{"id": 3, "name": "Australia", "slug": "australia"}], "production_dates": [{"date": "2020", "notes": "", "to_year": "2020"}], "labels": [57545]}, {"id": 118034, "acmi_id": "Z000183", "title": "Entities", "title_annotation": "", "slug": "entities", "creator_credit": "Greg More (OOM Creative), James Sandri (MORE Studio), Pete Brundle (MORE Studio), MORE Studio and OOM Creative", "credit_line": "", "headline_credit": "Australia, 2020", "video_links": [], "record_type": "work", "type": "Artwork", "is_on_display": true, "last_on_display_place": "ACMI: Gallery 1", "last_on_display_date": "2031-02-16", "is_context_indigenous": false, "material_description": "Data visualisation.", "unpublished": false, "external": false, "first_production_date": "2020-01-01T11:00:00+11:00", "commissioned": true, "public_domain": false, "external_references": [], "brief_description": "<p>Entities is a time-based data visualisation of visitors collecting objects and exploring Constellations. These actions are translated into graphical forms to show what’s being collected, as well as highlighting Constellations that share connections.</p>", "constellations_primary": [{"id": 294, "name": "Future visions", "description": "<i>Entities</i> is a time-based data visualisation of visitors collecting objects and exploring Constellations. These actions are translated into graphical forms to show what’s being collected, as well as highlighting Constellations that share connections."}], "constellations_other": [], "recommendations": [], "title_for_label": "<p>Entities</p>", "creator_credit_for_label": "<p>Greg More (OOM Creative), James Sandri (MORE Studio), Pete Brundle (MORE Studio), MORE Studio and OOM Creative</p>", "headline_credit_for_label": "<p>Australia, 2020</p>", "description": "<p>We leave a trace whenever we interact with a digital system: a thread of data that lingers like a ghost within a machine.</p>\n<p><i>Entities</i> is a time-based data visualisation of visitors collecting objects and exploring Constellations. These actions are translated into graphical forms to show what’s being collected, as well as highlighting Constellations that share connections. Each time an object is collected, the visualisation updates in real-time to create a dynamic living map of our visitors’ journey: the more people in the space, the more active it becomes. Created by code and contemporary web technologies, <i>Entities</i> encourages visitors to discover new objects and artworks by seeing what others are collecting in the gallery over time.</p>", "description_for_label": ["<p>We leave a trace whenever we interact with a digital system: a thread of data that lingers like a ghost within a machine.</p>\n<p><i>Entities</i> is a time-based data visualisation of visitors collecting objects and exploring Constellations. These actions are translated into graphical forms to show what’s being collected, as well as highlighting Constellations that share connections. Each time an object is collected, the visualisation updates in real-time to create a dynamic living map of our visitors’ journey: the more people in the space, the more active it becomes. Created by code and contemporary web technologies, <i>Entities</i> encourages visitors to discover new objects and artworks by seeing what others are collecting in the gallery over time.</p>"], "credit_line_for_label": "", "details": [{"label": "Curatorial section", "display_values": ["The Story of the Moving Image&nbsp;→ Constellation"]}, {"label": "Object Types", "display_values": ["Artwork"]}, {"label": "Materials", "display_values": ["Data visualisation."]}], "stats": {"tap_count": 159488}, "links": [], "creators_primary": [{"id": 2686589, "name": "Greg More (OOM Creative)", "creator_id": 84850, "creator_wikidata_id": null, "role": "creator", "role_id": 968, "is_primary": true}, {"id": 2686587, "name": "James Sandri (MORE Studio)", "creator_id": 84770, "creator_wikidata_id": null, "role": "creator", "role_id": 968, "is_primary": true}, {"id": 2686588, "name": "Pete Brundle (MORE Studio)", "creator_id": 84769, "creator_wikidata_id": null, "role": "creator", "role_id": 968, "is_primary": true}, {"id": 2686590, "name": "MORE Studio", "creator_id": 84771, "creator_wikidata_id": null, "role": "production company", "role_id": 941, "is_primary": true}, {"id": 2686591, "name": "OOM Creative", "creator_id": 84431, "creator_wikidata_id": null, "role": "production company", "role_id": 941, "is_primary": true}], "creators_other": [], "media_note": null, "holdings": [], "part_of": null, "parts": [], "part_siblings": [], "group": null, "group_works": [], "group_siblings": [], "source": {"name": "Vernon", "slug": "vernon"}, "source_identifier": "184198", "eaas_environment_id": null, "production_places": [{"id": 3, "name": "Australia", "slug": "australia"}], "production_dates": [{"date": "2020", "notes": "", "to_year": "2020"}], "labels": [57536]}, {"id": 118209, "acmi_id": "B2004395", "title": "Cyberthon Archives [documentation]", "title_annotation": "", "slug": "cyberthon-archives-documentation", "creator_credit": "", "credit_line": "", "headline_credit": "Australia, 1991-1996", "video_links": [], "record_type": "group", "type": "Object", "is_on_display": false, "last_on_display_place": null, "last_on_display_date": null, "is_context_indigenous": false, "material_description": "", "unpublished": false, "external": false, "first_production_date": null, "commissioned": false, "public_domain": false, "external_references": [], "brief_description": "<p>Cyberthon was a series of TV broadcast events initiated in the 1990&#8217;s in Melbourne, Australia. This collection contains photographs, images and documentation that accompany the moving content in the archive.</p>", "constellations_primary": [], "constellations_other": [], "recommendations": [], "title_for_label": "<p>Cyberthon Archives [documentation]</p>", "creator_credit_for_label": "", "headline_credit_for_label": "<p>Australia, 1991-1996</p>", "description": "<p>Cyberthon was a series of TV broadcast events initiated in the 1990&#8217;s in Melbourne, Australia. This collection contains photographs, images and documentation that accompany the moving content in the archive.</p>", "description_for_label": ["<p>Cyberthon was a series of TV broadcast events initiated in the 1990&#8217;s in Melbourne, Australia. This collection contains photographs, images and documentation that accompany the moving content in the archive.</p>"], "credit_line_for_label": "", "details": [{"label": "Subject category", "display_values": ["Documentation"]}, {"label": "Object Types", "display_values": ["html file (website component)/Digital", "Still image file/Digital"]}], "stats": {"tap_count": 0}, "links": [], "creators_primary": [], "creators_other": [{"id": 2686586, "name": "Adem Jaffers", "creator_id": 81893, "creator_wikidata_id": "Q121079496", "role": "contact", "role_id": 543, "is_primary": false}], "media_note": null, "holdings": [], "part_of": null, "parts": [], "part_siblings": [], "group": null, "group_works": [], "group_siblings": [], "source": {"name": "Vernon", "slug": "vernon"}, "source_identifier": "184197", "eaas_environment_id": null, "production_places": [{"id": 3, "name": "Australia", "slug": "australia"}], "production_dates": [{"date": "1991-1996", "notes": "", "to_year": "1991-1996"}], "labels": [57712]}, {"id": 118033, "acmi_id": "", "title": "Videogames supercut", "title_annotation": "", "slug": "videogames-supercut", "creator_credit": "ACMI", "credit_line": "", "headline_credit": "Australia, 2020", "video_links": [], "record_type": "work", "type": "Film", "is_on_display": true, "last_on_display_place": "ACMI: Gallery 1", "last_on_display_date": "2031-02-16", "is_context_indigenous": false, "material_description": "", "unpublished": false, "external": false, "first_production_date": "2020-01-01T11:00:00+11:00", "commissioned": false, "public_domain": false, "external_references": [], "brief_description": "<p>Today’s videogames focus as much on emotion as they do action. Through evolving technical expertise and the power of narrative, character and story are now as vital to a memorable gaming experience as ammo clips and power-ups.</p>", "constellations_primary": [{"id": 276, "name": "Action, emotion and videogames", "description": "More and more, videogames are beginning to favour emotion as much as action, just like their film and TV cousins."}], "constellations_other": [], "recommendations": [], "title_for_label": "<p>Videogames supercut</p>", "creator_credit_for_label": "<p>ACMI</p>", "headline_credit_for_label": "<p>Australia, 2020</p>", "description": "<p>Today’s videogames focus as much on emotion as they do action. Through evolving technical expertise and the power of narrative, character and story are now as vital to a memorable gaming experience as ammo clips and power-ups. This video interweaves scenes from AAA, indie games and everything in-between to explore the emotional impact of games, as well as the white-knuckle tension of battle, how time can be manipulated for dramatic effect and how artistic expressions like movement and dance are bringing a human element to gaming.</p>", "description_for_label": ["<p>Today’s videogames focus as much on emotion as they do action. Through evolving technical expertise and the power of narrative, character and story are now as vital to a memorable gaming experience as ammo clips and power-ups. This video interweaves scenes from AAA, indie games and everything in-between to explore the emotional impact of games, as well as the white-knuckle tension of battle, how time can be manipulated for dramatic effect and how artistic expressions like movement and dance are bringing a human element to gaming.</p>"], "credit_line_for_label": "", "details": [{"label": "Curatorial section", "display_values": ["The Story of the Moving Image&nbsp;→ Games Lab"]}, {"label": "Object Types", "display_values": ["Moving image file/Digital"]}], "stats": {"tap_count": 201007}, "links": [], "creators_primary": [{"id": 2686585, "name": "ACMI", "creator_id": 6272, "creator_wikidata_id": null, "role": "creator", "role_id": 968, "is_primary": true}], "creators_other": [], "media_note": null, "holdings": [], "part_of": null, "parts": [], "part_siblings": [], "group": null, "group_works": [], "group_siblings": [], "source": {"name": "Vernon", "slug": "vernon"}, "source_identifier": "184196", "eaas_environment_id": null, "production_places": [{"id": 3, "name": "Australia", "slug": "australia"}], "production_dates": [{"date": "2020", "notes": "", "to_year": "2020"}], "labels": [57535]}, {"id": 117995, "acmi_id": "", "title": "fork and spoon", "title_annotation": "", "slug": "fork-and-spoon", "creator_credit": "", "credit_line": "<p>ACMI Collection</p>", "headline_credit": "Australia, 2014", "video_links": [], "record_type": "work", "type": "Artwork", "is_on_display": true, "last_on_display_place": "ACMI: Gallery 1", "last_on_display_date": "2031-02-16", "is_context_indigenous": true, "material_description": "Mixed media", "unpublished": false, "external": false, "first_production_date": "2014-01-01T11:00:00+11:00", "commissioned": false, "public_domain": false, "external_references": [], "brief_description": "", "constellations_primary": [], "constellations_other": [], "recommendations": [], "title_for_label": "<p>fork and spoon</p>", "creator_credit_for_label": "", "headline_credit_for_label": "<p>Australia, 2014</p>", "description": "", "description_for_label": [], "credit_line_for_label": "<p>ACMI Collection</p>", "details": [{"label": "Curatorial section", "display_values": ["The Story of the Moving Image&nbsp;→ Moving Pictures&nbsp;→ MI-01. Light and Shadow&nbsp;→ MI-01-C01"]}, {"label": "Object Types", "display_values": ["Artwork"]}, {"label": "Materials", "display_values": ["Mixed media"]}], "stats": {"tap_count": 2}, "links": [], "creators_primary": [], "creators_other": [], "media_note": null, "holdings": [], "part_of": null, "parts": [], "part_siblings": [], "group": null, "group_works": [], "group_siblings": [], "source": {"name": "Vernon", "slug": "vernon"}, "source_identifier": "183984", "eaas_environment_id": null, "production_places": [{"id": 3, "name": "Australia", "slug": "australia"}], "production_dates": [{"date": "2014", "notes": "", "to_year": "2014"}], "labels": [57497]}, {"id": 117996, "acmi_id": "", "title": "ship hat", "title_annotation": "", "slug": "ship-hat", "creator_credit": "", "credit_line": "<p>ACMI Collection</p>", "headline_credit": "Australia, 2014", "video_links": [], "record_type": "work", "type": "Artwork", "is_on_display": true, "last_on_display_place": "ACMI: Gallery 1", "last_on_display_date": "2031-02-16", "is_context_indigenous": true, "material_description": "Mixed media", "unpublished": false, "external": false, "first_production_date": "2014-01-01T11:00:00+11:00", "commissioned": false, "public_domain": false, "external_references": [], "brief_description": "", "constellations_primary": [], "constellations_other": [], "recommendations": [], "title_for_label": "<p>ship hat</p>", "creator_credit_for_label": "", "headline_credit_for_label": "<p>Australia, 2014</p>", "description": "", "description_for_label": [], "credit_line_for_label": "<p>ACMI Collection</p>", "details": [{"label": "Curatorial section", "display_values": ["The Story of the Moving Image&nbsp;→ Moving Pictures&nbsp;→ MI-01. Light and Shadow&nbsp;→ MI-01-C01"]}, {"label": "Object Types", "display_values": ["Artwork"]}, {"label": "Materials", "display_values": ["Mixed media"]}], "stats": {"tap_count": 0}, "links": [], "creators_primary": [], "creators_other": [], "media_note": null, "holdings": [], "part_of": null, "parts": [], "part_siblings": [], "group": null, "group_works": [], "group_siblings": [], "source": {"name": "Vernon", "slug": "vernon"}, "source_identifier": "183983", "eaas_environment_id": null, "production_places": [{"id": 3, "name": "Australia", "slug": "australia"}], "production_dates": [{"date": "2014", "notes": "", "to_year": "2014"}], "labels": [57498]}, {"id": 117994, "acmi_id": "", "title": "down among the wild men / colonial imagination", "title_annotation": "", "slug": "down-among-the-wild-men-colonial-imagination", "creator_credit": "Ali Gumillya Baker", "credit_line": "<p>ACMI Collection</p>", "headline_credit": "Mirning, 2014", "video_links": [], "record_type": "group", "type": "Artwork", "is_on_display": true, "last_on_display_place": "ACMI: Gallery 1", "last_on_display_date": "2031-02-16", "is_context_indigenous": true, "material_description": "Video loop, artist and Michael Bonner (performer)", "unpublished": false, "external": false, "first_production_date": "2014-01-01T11:00:00+11:00", "commissioned": false, "public_domain": false, "external_references": [], "brief_description": "<p>Shadow play, projection and performance combine to question our history and shift the colonial gaze in Ali Gumillya Baker’s mixed media video installation.</p>", "constellations_primary": [{"id": 298, "name": "The drama and nuance of silhouette", "description": "Ali Gumillya Baker uses silhouette to evocative effect in her work reimagining the colonial gaze. The lighting technique has long been employed by filmmakers for its ability to dramatically convey a wide variety of emotions in everything from film noir to animation and whimsy."}], "constellations_other": [{"id": 303, "name": "Keep the fire burning", "description": "<i>Yanmeeyarr</i>, meaning ‘flickering in firelight’, shares how light and shadow are at the core of the moving image. It reflects the past, present and future of stories told by First Peoples utilising these elements, as well as bringing to light stories that have, for too long, been kept in the dark."}], "recommendations": [], "title_for_label": "<p>down among the wild men / colonial imagination</p>", "creator_credit_for_label": "<p>Ali Gumillya Baker</p>", "headline_credit_for_label": "<p>Mirning, 2014</p>", "description": "<p>Shadow play, projection and performance combine to question our history and shift the colonial gaze in Ali Gumillya Baker’s mixed media video installation.</p>\n<p>“This is a violent black tragedy, a cathartic melodrama. Dressed in a tall ship hat pretending to be a colonialist, the Mirning artist writes with her feather quill back to the colonial-mother-monarch of her times ‘down among the wild men’. From the shade of the gum tree. At the same time as her chronicling, she is attacked by a wild man, (fellow sovereign Yanyuwa artist), who with a super large fork pretend stabs her in the back and the pretend explorer/tall ship coloniser collapses. Even the trees are scared of us blackfellas the hand holding the tree is shaking in fear. The background soundtrack that the viewer cannot hear is us all laughing maniacally at the re-enactment of the anthropological and colonial gaze.” - Ali Gumillya Baker</p>", "description_for_label": ["<p>Shadow play, projection and performance combine to question our history and shift the colonial gaze in Ali Gumillya Baker’s mixed media video installation.</p>\n<p>“This is a violent black tragedy, a cathartic melodrama. Dressed in a tall ship hat pretending to be a colonialist, the Mirning artist writes with her feather quill back to the colonial-mother-monarch of her times ‘down among the wild men’. From the shade of the gum tree. At the same time as her chronicling, she is attacked by a wild man, (fellow sovereign Yanyuwa artist), who with a super large fork pretend stabs her in the back and the pretend explorer/tall ship coloniser collapses. Even the trees are scared of us blackfellas the hand holding the tree is shaking in fear. The background soundtrack that the viewer cannot hear is us all laughing maniacally at the re-enactment of the anthropological and colonial gaze.” - Ali Gumillya Baker</p>"], "credit_line_for_label": "<p>ACMI Collection</p>", "details": [{"label": "Subject category", "display_values": ["Digital Art"]}, {"label": "Curatorial sections", "display_values": ["The Story of the Moving Image&nbsp;→ Moving Pictures&nbsp;→ MI-01. Light and Shadow&nbsp;→ MI-01-AV03", "The Story of the Moving Image&nbsp;→ Moving Pictures&nbsp;→ MI-01. Light and Shadow&nbsp;→ MI-01-C01"]}, {"label": "Object Types", "display_values": ["Artwork"]}, {"label": "Materials", "display_values": ["Video loop, artist and Michael Bonner (performer)"]}], "stats": {"tap_count": 365008}, "links": [], "creators_primary": [{"id": 2686528, "name": "Ali Gumillya Baker", "creator_id": 72007, "creator_wikidata_id": null, "role": "artist", "role_id": 505, "is_primary": true}], "creators_other": [], "media_note": null, "holdings": [], "part_of": null, "parts": [], "part_siblings": [], "group": null, "group_works": [], "group_siblings": [], "source": {"name": "Vernon", "slug": "vernon"}, "source_identifier": "183982", "eaas_environment_id": null, "production_places": [{"id": 282, "name": "Mirning", "slug": "mirning"}], "production_dates": [{"date": "2014", "notes": "", "to_year": "2014"}], "labels": [57496]}, {"id": 120326, "acmi_